              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The long hard fall</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Marvel's journey through the ’80s and ’90s was a rollercoaster. <strong>Ronald Perelman bought the company for $82.5 million in 1989 and took it public in 1991</strong>. The early ’90s were a golden era, fueled by the success of Spider-Man and X-Men. Fans went wild over holographic covers, embossed pages, and collectible trading cards, scrambling to buy multiple copies. <strong>Flush with cash, Perelman embarked on a $700 million acquisition spree</strong> ($1.6 billion today), buying trading card companies like Fleer and SkyBox and a 46% stake in ToyBiz. Soon, the market became flooded with endless titles and variants while quality took a backseat. Marvel's attempt to capitalize with more memorabilia only worsened the situation. By 1993, the comic book market crashed, with sales plummeting 70%.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">By 1996, Marvel's stock plunged from $35.75 to just $2.38; the company was $610 million in debt ($1.3 billion today). Perelman’s desperate attempt to file for <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-11-01-2025-4-chapter-11-bankruptcy" target="_blank">Chapter 11 bankruptcy</a> without shareholder approval led to legal turmoil. Perelman was ousted, and ToyBiz executives Isaac Perlmutter and Avi Arad took over the reins of Marvel in 1997 after a contentious and lengthy legal battle.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Last straw</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In the early 2000s, Marvel was drowning in debt and resorted to <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-11-01-2025-5-licensing-film-rights" target="_blank">licensing film rights</a> for its characters, leading to Sony owning Spider-Man and Fox controlling the X-Men and The Fantastic Four. The deals were painfully lopsided. For instance, The Blade (1998) movie raked in $70 million ($136 million today), yet Marvel pocketed a measly $25,000. Sony’s first two Spider-Man films earned nearly $2 billion ($3.3 billion today), yet Marvel's share was just $62 million.</p>
          </mj-text> 

          <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-jan-11-2.jpg" alt="Innovation repurposed" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 2003, talent agent <strong>David Maisel proposed a bold idea: Marvel should produce its own films instead of licensing characters</strong>, keeping creative control and profits. To fund this gamble, Marvel secured a $525 million loan from Merrill Lynch, using the rights to 10 iconic characters as collateral, including Ant-Man, Black Panther, Doctor Strange, Captain America, and the Avengers. <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-11-01-2025-6-despite-initial-doubts" target="_blank">Despite initial doubts</a> and around 30 screenwriters turning down the project, the film Iron Man was released in 2008, starring Robert Downey Jr. It was a massive success, grossing over $585 million globally ($871 million today) and kickstarting the Marvel Cinematic Universe.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><strong>By 2009, Disney had acquired Marvel for a staggering $4.3 billion</strong>. With 34 films and countless hit shows today, Marvel is valued at $54 billion (2024) and stands as Disney’s crown jewel. Marvel’s story proves that even in the darkest hours, the greatest comebacks are possible.</p>
          </mj-text>

      </mj-column>
